\section{Resolved SharePoint addresses}

SharePoint's REST endpoints do not use the browser URLs directly. Most of
the time they want a site URL and a server-relative path, but some browser
links only expose a file id. We therefore keep the resolved address in a
small immutable object that can represent both cases.
<<classes>>=
@dataclasses.dataclass(frozen=True)
class SharePointLocation:
  """Resolved SharePoint address for one file or folder."""

  site_url: str
  server_relative_path: Optional[str] = None
  file_id: Optional[str] = None

  <<[[SharePointLocation]] methods>>
@

When we do have a concrete path, the file name is the last component. That
is the right default for [[get]], because it matches the remote object rather
than inventing a local naming convention.
<<[[SharePointLocation]] methods>>=
@property
def name(self):
  """Return the file name part of the resolved path."""
  if self.server_relative_path is None:
    raise ValueError("SharePoint location does not expose a file path")
  return pathlib.PurePosixPath(self.server_relative_path).name
@

Uploads need the containing folder separately from the file name, since the
SharePoint [[Files/add]] endpoint addresses the folder and the new file name
independently.
<<[[SharePointLocation]] methods>>=
@property
def folder_relative_path(self):
  """Return the parent folder of the resolved file path."""
  if self.server_relative_path is None:
    raise ValueError("SharePoint location does not expose a file path")
  return str(pathlib.PurePosixPath(self.server_relative_path).parent)
@

Folder listings still need the owning document library separately, because
[[RenderListDataAsStream]] is rooted there rather than at the child folder.
The library root is the first three components of the server-relative path.
<<[[SharePointLocation]] methods>>=
@property
def library_relative_path(self):
  """Return the document-library root for the resolved path."""
  if self.server_relative_path is None:
    raise ValueError("SharePoint location does not expose a library path")
  parts = self.server_relative_path.lstrip("/").split("/")
  if len(parts) < 3:
    raise ValueError("SharePoint path does not contain a document library")
  return "/" + "/".join(parts[:3])
@

