The session exposes three layers of listing: a simple [[ls]] view, a detailed
view for long listings and trees, and a site-root view that expands to the
visible document libraries.

We branch on whether the URL is a site root, not on how many libraries it
happens to contain. A site root has no single folder to list, so [[ls]]
always shows its document libraries as directories --- even a site with
exactly one library. Deciding by library count instead would make a
one-library site silently descend into that library, so the same command
would behave differently from site to site; keying on the site root keeps
[[ls]] consistent and matches the long and tree views, which also iterate
libraries.
<<[[OneDriveSession]] methods>>=
def list_by_url(self, url: str) -> list:
  """List the direct children of the folder addressed by ``url``."""
  location = parse_sharepoint_folder_url(url)
  if _is_site_root_path(location.server_relative_path):
    return [("dir", label)
            for label, _location in self.iter_folder_locations(url)]
  entries = [_list_data_entry(row)
             for row in _list_data_rows(self._render_list_data(location))]
  entries.sort(key=lambda entry: (entry[0], entry[1].casefold(), entry[1]))
  return entries
@

Site roots are special because the user has not picked a document library yet.
In that case we resolve to the visible libraries instead of pretending there is
one folder there.
<<[[OneDriveSession]] methods>>=
def iter_folder_locations(self, url: str) -> list:
  """Return the resolved folder targets addressed by ``url``."""
  location = parse_sharepoint_folder_url(url)
  if _is_site_root_path(location.server_relative_path):
    libraries = self._get_document_libraries(location)
    return [
        (library["title"],
         SharePointLocation(site_url=location.site_url,
                            server_relative_path=library["path"]))
        for library in libraries
    ]
  return [(_location_label(location), location)]
